default&#xa0;defaultResponses to Committee’s Lines of Inquirydefault&#xa0;default2. (Qdefault.5default)default default“defaultThe level of ambition in the programme to establish protected areas (including MCZs), compared with the need for biodiversity protection.default”default&#xa0;
default2.1 The Committee’s scrutiny of the “level of ambition” is the most pertinent point in the Inquiry. MCS believe that the present level of ambition falls considerably below what is needed to achieve Government’s stated vision of “clean, healthy, safe, productive, biologically diverse oceans and seas”. 
default&#xa0;
default2.2 The need for better protection of marine biodiversity has never been greater, to halt its decline and ensure the sustainability of the already overstretched goods and services provided by our seas. The overwhelming evidence of the decline in our marine biodiversity is detailed later in this submission. However, we should not loose sight that the very stimulus for the MCZ policy was an assessment - principally through the 
defaultReview of Marine Nature Conservation 
defaultand later 
defaultCharting Progress 
defaultand 
defaultCharting Progress 2
default reports - that the “costs of inaction” were unacceptably high. This demand for better protection and management is not presently matched sufficiently by a supply of political will to deliver a full network. Reference to “political will” in this submission is made not solely in relation to Defra, but more broadly to the Coalition Government. We believe political will was reduced because:
default&#xa0;
default(a)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn the political climate of austerity, Government has been blinded by minimising short term costs, however small, thereby disregarding the huge long term gains.
default&#xa0;
default(b)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGovernment has overestimated what is already protected in MPAs. 
default&#xa0;
defaultMPAs &amp; Politics of Austeritydefault2.3 The designation of a full network of MPAs is presently defined principally by the aim of minimising what is viewed as undue burden on the status quo for industry. This is clearly shown by the fact that when consulting on the 31MCZs proposed in the first tranche, the Government Impact Assessment
