default4.4 Government’s statutory government conservation bodies - JNCC and Natural England - engaged substantial outside expertise in the latest scientific understanding and global best practice in creating the design principles set out in the 
defaultEcological Network Guidance
default 
default(ENG). The ENG represented a world-class process, the outcome of which could be a world-class network of marine protection. 
default&#xa0;
default4.5 
defaultThese first 27 MCZS alone will not deliver the recovery of English seas that the Marine and Coastal Access Act 2009 was passed to achieve.
default Networks of marine protected areas - as opposed to isolated or scattered protection - are necessary in order to sustain habitats and species at large spatial scales over the long term. They are designed so as to represent the full spectrum of biodiversity, to ensure protected areas are of sufficient size and coverage to maintain viable populations, and that they are close enough to be mutually supporting through exchange of wildlife and their offspring. 
